1️⃣ Input & Output in C
🧠 Mental Model

Think of a program like a conversation:

Output → Program speaks

Input → User replies

Without input/output → program is useless (no interaction)

🔹 Output → printf()

You already saw:

printf("Hello");

👉 It prints text on screen.

📌 Printing Variables
int age = 21;
printf("%d", age);

👉 %d tells C: “expect an integer”

🔍 Common Format Specifiers
Type	Format
int	%d
float	%f
char	%c
🔹 Input → scanf()

This is where most students get confused. Let's simplify.

int age;
scanf("%d", &age);
🧠 Why &age (VERY IMPORTANT)

This is where real understanding begins.

Think like this:

👉 Variable = box
👉 & = address of the box

📦 Real-world analogy

Imagine:

age = your house

&age = your house address

When you say:

scanf("%d", &age);

You are telling the computer:

👉 “Go to this address and store the value there”

❌ If you write:
scanf("%d", age);

👉 You're giving the value, not the location → error

✅ Full Example
#include <stdio.h>

int main()
{
    int age;

    printf("Enter your age: ");
    scanf("%d", &age);

    printf("Your age is %d", age);

    return 0;
}
🧠 Why Input/Output Works

printf → sends data from program → screen

scanf → takes data from user → memory

🔗 Connection to What You Know

Python:

age = int(input())

Java:

Scanner sc = new Scanner(System.in);
int age = sc.nextInt();

C:

scanf("%d", &age);

👉 Same idea, but C is low-level → needs memory address

🧠 Memory Trick

👉 printf → print (output)
👉 scanf → scan (input)
👉 & → “Where to store?” (address)

2️⃣ Operators in C

Now we learn how C thinks and makes decisions.

🧠 Mental Model

Operators are like:

👉 tools to perform actions

Example:

+ → add

> → compare

&& → check multiple conditions

🔹 Types of Operators
1. Arithmetic Operators
+  -  *  /  %

Example:

int a = 10, b = 3;

printf("%d", a + b); // 13
printf("%d", a % b); // 1 (remainder)
📌 Why % (modulus) matters

Used in:

even/odd check

cyclic problems

hashing

🔹 2. Relational Operators

Used for comparison

>  <  >=  <=  ==  !=

Example:

int a = 5, b = 10;

printf("%d", a < b); // 1 (true)

👉 In C:

1 = true

0 = false

🔹 3. Logical Operators

Used for combining conditions

&&  (AND)
||  (OR)
!   (NOT)
Example:
int age = 20;

if(age > 18 && age < 25)
{
    printf("Eligible");
}

👉 Both conditions must be true

🧠 Why Operators Work This Way

Computers only understand:

0 (false)
1 (true)

So all decisions are converted into:

👉 binary logic

🔗 Connection to What You Know

Same in:

Java

C++

Python

But C directly works closer to machine logic

🧠 Memory Trick

Think:

👉 Arithmetic → calculate
👉 Relational → compare
👉 Logical → combine decisions

🔎 Interview Insight
Question 1

Why do we use & in scanf?

Answer:

Because scanf needs the memory address to store input.

Question 2

What is difference between = and ==?

👉 = → assignment
👉 == → comparison

